'''''A Thousand and One Wives''''' ({{lang-he|אלף נשותיו של נפתלי סימן טוב}}, [[romanization of Hebrew|tr.]] '''''Elef Neshotav Shel Naftali Siman-Tov''''', literally "Naftali Siman-Tov's Thousand Wives") is a [[1989 in film|1989]] [[cinema of Israel|Israeli]] [[independent film|independent]] [[underground film|underground]] dramatic-historical [[art film]] directed by [[Michal Bat-Adam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ictd.co.il/%D7%9E%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%9C-%D7%91%D7%AA-%D7%90%D7%93%D7%9D/%D7%90%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%95%D7%AA|script-title=he:מיכל בת־אדם|last=Sason|first=Yasmin|last2=Parkhomovsky|first2=Marat|date=20 December 2010|website={{ill|Israeli Cinema Testimonial Database|he|מאגר העדויות של הקולנוע הישראלי}}|language=Hebrew|access-date=31 March 2017}}</ref>

==Synopsis==
In the [[Bukharim quarter]], [[Jerusalem]], during the 1920s, merchant Naftali Siman-Tov ({{ill|Yossi Pollak|he|יוסי פולק}}) is a wealthy middle-aged widower, all of whose previous wives have died under mysterious circumstances. He fears getting married again due to believing that he is cursed. A local matchmaker, Arotchas ({{ill|Salim Daw|he|סלים דאו|fr}}), with the help of some old ladies, pressures him to get married again nonetheless, and, eventually, he marries Flora ([[Rita (Israeli singer)|Rita Jahanforuz]]), a naïve 24-year-old virgin. However, in order not to bestow his alleged curse upon her, he avoids all physical touch. Flora gets pregnant as a result of sleeping with a local textile salesman, Hamedian ({{ill|Jonathan Cherchi|he|יונתן צ'רצ'י}}), and, Naftali, unable to bear the shame, becomes violent toward his young wife.<ref>{{cite news|last=Israel|first=Yael|date=5 May 1989|script-title=he:הולכת אחרי חושיה|trans-title=Going After Her Senses|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0160/01600576.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Al HaMishmar]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=22 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shuv|first=Yael|date=5 May 1989|script-title=he:אומרים לי לשחק קטן|trans-title=I Was Told to Play Small Roles|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0160/01600585.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Davar]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=22 March 2017}}</ref>

==Reception==
Writing in ''[[Haaretz]]'', critic {{ill|Uri Klein|he|אורי קליין}} opined that [[Rita (Israeli singer)|Rita Jahanforuz]] "adds to this film a significant amount of humanity and humor, and, she has a natural filmic presence,"<ref>{{cite news|last=Klein|first=Uri|date=11 May 1989|script-title=he:הפוטנציאל של ריטה|trans-title=Rita's Potential|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0160/01600603.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Haaretz]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=22 March 2017}}</ref> while ''[[Yedioth Ahronoth]]'' critic {{ill|Nachman Ingber|he|נחמן אינגבר}} wrote that the film presents "a cornucopia of beautiful colors, [showing] a [[Jerusalem]] of towels, handsome tools, and, scarfs, really a wonderful parade of lots of tradition, customs, and, folklore, representing all [[Twelve Tribes of Israel]], as if it were a beautiful exhibition by [[Maskit]], with a well-spoken text,"<ref>{{cite news|last=Ingber|first=Nachman|date=12 May 1989|script-title=he:אלף בעיותיה של בת־אדם|trans-title=Bat-Adam's Thousand Problems|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0160/01600601.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Yedioth Ahronoth]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=22 March 2017}}</ref> ''[[Davar]]'' critic {{ill|Oshra Schwartz|he|אושרה שוורץ}} noted that the film's main achievement is its treatment of color and light, namely, that the cinematography "creates an almost perfect match between the view that can be seen through the vast Jerusalemite windows (in which the characters walk) and the large rooms within the old tastefully and colorfully decorated stone-made houses,"<ref>{{cite news|last=Schwartz|first=Oshra|date=14 May 1989|script-title=he:על החלטות נכונות ושגויות|trans-title=On Correct and Incorrect Decisions|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0160/01600607.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Davar]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=22 March 2017}}</ref> and ''[[Al HaMishmar]]'' critic {{ill|Yael Israel|he|יעל ישראל}} underscored that the film is [[Michal Bat-Adam]]'s "best and most wholesome film" to date, due to its "reliable and reserved cinematic language creating a correct historical environment and utilizing glowing and careful acting."<ref>{{cite news|last=Israel|first=Yael|date=19 June 1989|script-title=he:סיפור פשוט|trans-title=A Simple Story|url=http://idea.cinema.co.il/ideawebinter/multimedia_11/0160/01600598.pdf|language=Hebrew|work=[[Al HaMishmar]]|location=Tel Aviv|access-date=22 March 2017}}</ref>

