{{Infobox person | name = George J. Felos | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = March 1952 | birth_place = New York | nationality = American | education = [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]], [[Boston University School of Law]] | alma_mater = | occupation = Lawyer | years_active = | employer = | website = }}
'''George James Felos''' (born March 1952) is an American lawyer specializing in [[right-to-die]] cases. He is best known for representing [[Terri Schiavo]]'s husband Michael.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tubbs|first=Sharon|title=The spirit and the law|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/052501/Floridian/The_spirit_and_the_la.shtml|accessdate=26 November 2012|newspaper=St Petersburg Times (Florida)|date=May 25, 2001}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Raised Greek-Orthodox, Felos graduated from [[Boston University]] School of Law with a [[Juris Doctor]] in 1976. He was admitted to the Florida Bar in 1977.
{{Terri Schiavo}}
==Career== In 1990 he represented the family of Estelle Browning in an earlier right-to-die case at the Florida Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite book|last=Colby|first=William H|title=Unplugged: Reclaiming Our Right to Die in America|year=2007|publisher=AMACOM Div American Mgmt Assn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aGpJIXhxZhUC&lpg=PA15&dq=george%20felos%20Estelle%20Browning&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q=george%20felos%20Estelle%20Browning&f=false|page=15}}</ref> Browning while still healthy had written a [[living will]] asking not to be artificially kept alive, before suffering a serious [[stroke]] which had left her in a nursing home reliant on a feeding tube for nearly 3 years; a judge had prevented the will being enacted, but Felos litigated the case even after Browning's death in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|title=Florida Woman Dies Attached to a Tube; Legal Fight Goes On|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/07/19/us/florida-woman-dies-attached-to-a-tube-legal-fight-goes-on.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 19, 1989}}</ref> In 1990 in a "landmark ruling" the Florida Supreme Court decided in Browning's favor, ruling that the permanently incapacitated need not be force-fed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Right-to-die law defined by local case|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/10/13/Tampabay/Right_to_die_law_defi.shtml|newspaper=St Petersburg Times (Florida)|date=October 13, 2003}}</ref>
His conduct in the Schiavo case caused controversy, because he had Terry Schiavo moved to the Woodside Hospice, Florida, where until recently he had been chairman of the board.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Didion|first=Joan|title=The Case of Theresa Schiavo|journal=New York Review of Books|date=Jun 9, 2005|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2005/jun/09/the-case-of-theresa-schiavo/?pagination=false}}</ref>
He is also the author of ''Litigation as Spiritual Practice'' (Blue Dolphin Publishing), which combined discussion of legal practice with spiritual reflections on meditation and new-age religious beliefs.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pfeiffer |first=Eric |title=Odd Felos |url=http://old.nationalreview.com/comment/pfeiffer200503301030.asp |newspaper=National Review |date=March 30, 2005 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}
