[[Image:Funeral Carriage.JPG|thumb|[[Hearse|Funeral Carriage]]]] [[Image:Embalming_fluid.jpg|thumb|Early [[embalming]] fluid]] [[Image:Lincoln's coffin, replica.JPG|thumb|[[Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln's]] coffin, replica]]
The '''Museum of Funeral Customs''' was located at 1440 Monument Ave. in [[Springfield, Illinois]], USA. It featured exhibits dealing with American [[funeral|funerary]] and [[mourning]] customs. The [[museum]] was near [[Oak Ridge Cemetery]], the site of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s [[Lincoln's Tomb|tomb]]. Collections at the museum included a re-created 1920s [[embalming]] room, [[coffin]]s and funeral paraphernalia from various cultures and times, examples of [[post-mortem photography]], and a scale model of Lincoln's [[funeral train]]. The museum hosted tours and special events and provided resources to scholars who are researching funeral customs. A gift shop provided books and funeral-related gifts, including coffin-shaped keychains and chocolates. The museum was closed in March 2009 due to poor attendance and handling of the museum's trust fund.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/09/us/09funeral.html?_r=1&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1254586499-/QycUK/kcjvwM/iqRsqGfA</ref><ref>[http://www.thelastromance.com.my/ The Last Romance] - {{cite web|url=http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/12175 |title=Museum of Funeral Customs - Closed, Springfield, Illinois |publisher=Roadsideamerica.com |date= |accessdate=2013-02-09}}</ref> The contents of the collection were transferred to the Kibbe Hancock Heritage Museum in [[Carthage, Illinois]] in February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Swearingen|first=Joy|title=Priceless museum pieces come to Kibbe; Artifacts include Lincoln funeral history, replicas|url=http://www.journalpilot.com/articles/2011/02/01/news/news1.txt|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130629141842/http://www.journalpilot.com/articles/2011/02/01/news/news1.txt|dead-url=yes|archive-date=29 June 2013|accessdate=12 Apr 2011|newspaper=Hancock County Journal-Pilot|date=1 Feb 2011}}</ref>
The home of the former museum reopened in March 2016 as the [[Springfield and Central Illinois African-American History Museum]], a museum of the black heritage of central Illinois.
