{{Infobox QuebecMNA | name= Yves Bolduc | image= | caption= | cabinet= Minister of Health and Social Services | birth_date= {{birth date and age|1957|3|6}} | birth_place= [[Alma, Quebec]] | death_date= | death_place= | profession= general practitioner, coroner | party=[[Quebec Liberal Party]] | party colour= Liberal | residence= | office=Member of the [[National Assembly of Quebec]] for [[Jean-Talon]] | term_start= September 30, 2008 | term_end= February 26, 2015 | predecessor= [[Philippe Couillard]] | successor= [[Sébastien Proulx]] | portfolio= | footnotes= | term_start2= | term_end2= | predecessor2= | successor2= | spouse= Chantal Trépanier |}}
'''Yves Bolduc''' (born March 6, 1957 in [[Alma, Quebec]]) is a doctor and politician in the [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[Quebec]]. He was named the new Minister of Health and Social Services of Quebec on June 25, 2008 succeeding [[Philippe Couillard]] who resigned on the same day following five years as Minister for that portfolio.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/Politique/2008/06/25/003-bolduc-ministre-sante.shtml Gouvernement Charest : Bolduc succède à Couillard | Politique | Radio-Canada.ca<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and was member of the [[National Assembly of Quebec]] of the [[Quebec City]] riding of [[Jean-Talon]]. He is a member of the [[Quebec Liberal Party]].
==Education and professional career== Bolduc holds a [[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.), a [[master's degree]] from the [[École nationale d'administration publique]] and a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[bioethics]] from the [[Université du Québec à Chicoutimi]]. He started his studies at the [[Laval University|Université Laval]] where he obtained a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[health sciences]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plq.org/bolduc/biographie.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 3, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013012953/http://www.plq.org/bolduc/biographie.php |archivedate=October 13, 2008 }}</ref>
Bolduc worked as a [[general practitioner]] since 1981 and as a [[coroner]] since 1985. He was also the general manager of the Health and Social services center of the [[La Vallée-de-l'Or Regional County Municipality|Vallée-de-l'Or]] in the [[Abitibi-Témiscamingue]] region and ran the professional services department of the Lac Saint-Jean Health and Social Services Center for fourteen years. He was also president of the Association des Conseils de médecins, dentistes et pharmaciens du Québec and a member of the Alma Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.canoe.com/infos/quebeccanada/archives/2008/06/20080626-052901.html Canoe – Infos – Québec-Canada: Un autre missionnaire<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
Over his years as a practitioner, Bolduc was more specialized in service accessibility, and he recently implemented methods inspired from the [[Toyota]] assembly line to better manage the operating room at the [[Val-d'Or]] Hospital.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[http://www.radio-canada.ca/regions/abitibi/2008/06/21/002-csss-valdor.shtml L'approche Toyota<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==Political career==
Bolduc ran as a member of the Liberal Party during the [[Quebec general election, 2007|2007 general election]] in the riding of [[Lac-Saint-Jean (electoral district)|Lac Saint-Jean]]. However, he was defeated by the [[Parti Québécois]] candidate [[Alexandre Cloutier]].<ref>[http://www.cyberpresse.ca/article/20080625/CPACTUALITES/80625059/6488/CPACTUALITES Rémi Nadeau et Martin Ouellet : Yves Bolduc succède à Philippe Couillard | Actualités | Cyberpresse<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The PQ swept the entire [[Saguenay–Lac-Saint-Jean]] region in that election.
By becoming a member of the [[Jean Charest]] cabinet, Bolduc became the first unelected Minister since the PQ's [[David Levine (medical administrator)|David Levine]], who was named delegate minister for health in the [[Bernard Landry]] cabinet in 2002. About only 40 other non-elected members since 1874 were named to Cabinet.<ref name=autogenerated2 />
Bolduc ran in a by-election on September 29 in the [[Jean-Talon]] riding left vacant by the departure of Couillard. Bolduc was easily elected, receiving 58% of the vote.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>http://lcn.canoe.ca/lcn/infos/national/archives/2008/09/20080929-211449.html</ref>
==Controversy== While Quebec Education Minister in 2015, Mr. Bolduc publicly defended the policy which allowed a school administrator in Quebec City to strip search a 15-year-old student.<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/yves-bolduc-says-teen-strip-search-allowed-in-high-schools-1.2960521</ref> The statements have caused outrage among some Quebecers who have started a petition asking for his resignation.<ref>http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/yves-bolduc-backtracks-on-school-strip-search-policy-1.2961320</ref> He later announced a re-examination of the rules, stating an independent party will be investigating the situation.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2015/02/18/quebec-reviewing-policies-after-school-strip-search-of-girl-15.html Policy review news story]</ref>
Following much speculation, Bolduc announced his resignation as both Education Minister and MNA on February 26, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Authier|first=Philip|url=http://montrealgazette.com/news/quebec/education-minister-yves-bolduc-poised-to-resign-reports-say|title= Yves Bolduc turns his back on politics, heads back to medicine|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=February 26, 2015|accessdate=February 26, 2015}}</ref>
